    <!-- BOX MODEL EXAMPLE 1 -->
    <section>
      <h1>Box Model</h1>
      <ul>
        <li>Wrapper for all our HTML elements</li>
        <li>Each HTML element we have on the page is made up of 4 main components</li>
        <li>Margin, Border, Padding, Content</li>
        <li>These 4 properties relate to each other</li>
        <li>Can modify all these properties using CSS</li>
        <li>Each element has a default property</li>
        <li>The box model helps you visualize where your elements sit on your webpage and how they are spaced from each other</li>
      </ul>

      <div id="box1">
        <p>content for box 1</p>
      </div>

      <div id="box2">
        <p>content for box 2</p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <hr>
    <br>

    <!-- BLOCK, INLINE, INLINE-BLOCK -->
    <section>
      <br>
      <h1>Block, Inline, Inline-Block</h1>
      <ul>
        <li>Every HTML element has a default display property</li>
        <li>CSS can override this default property</li>
        <li>Before flex box, we had to use these properties to create our layouts</li>
        <li>Challenging to create responsive websites with modern layouts</li>
      </ul>
      <br>
    </section>

    <hr>
    <br>

    <!-- BLOCK -->
    <section>
      <br>
      <h1>Block</h1>
      <br>
      <div class="block-elements">
        <h4>Block Elements</h4>
        <p>Other examples of block elements: p, h1, h2, h3, h4, h5, h6, ul, ol...etc</p>
        <ul>
          <li>start a new line (h1, p, div)</li>
          <li>take up entire width, that's why they flow top to bottom</li>
          <li>does not allow left or right elements of them</li>
          <li>can set specific widths and heights</li>
        </ul>
        <br>
        <div class="div-block">
          <p>div block</p>
        </div>
        <div class="div-block">
          <p>div block</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <br>
    </section>

    <hr>
    <br>

    <!-- INLINE -->
    <section>
      <br>
      <h1>Inline</h1>
      <br>
      <div class="inline-elements">
        <h4>Inline Elements</h4>
        <p>Other examples of inline elements: span, em, strong</p>
        <ul>
          <li>take up only as much space as they need for content</li>
          <li>flow within the text, from left to right</li>
          <li>cannot set height and width</li>
          <li>continue on the same line as other elements (strong, em, span)</li>
        </ul>
